<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Physics" id="109" name="Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Who proposed the photon theory of light to explain the photoelectric effect?</text>
            <option id="A">Einstein</option><option id="B">Newton</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Einstein suggested that light acts as discrete packets of energy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenomenon of emission of electrons from a metal surface when light of suitable frequency falls on it is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Photoelectric effect</option><option id="B">Thermionic emission</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Direct conversion of light energy to electrical energy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Minimum energy required to just eject an electron from a metal surface is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Work Function (Φ₀)</option><option id="B">Ionization energy</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dependent on the material of the surface.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The SI unit of Work Function is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Joule (J) or eV</option><option id="B">Volt</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>It is energy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relation between Work Function Φ₀ and threshold frequency f₀ is Φ₀ = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h f₀</option><option id="B">h / f₀</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>h is Planck's constant.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Threshold frequency is the minimum frequency below which ____ occurs.</text>
            <option id="A">No photoelectron emission</option><option id="B">Emission happens always</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic of the metal.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>What is the value of Planck's constant h?</text>
            <option id="A">6.63 x 10^-34 J s</option><option id="B">6.63 x 10^-27 J s</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fundamental constant in quantum mechanics.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Einstein's photoelectric equation is Kmax = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h f - Φ₀</option><option id="B">h f + Φ₀</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy conservation: Incident energy = Work function + Max KE.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Maximum kinetic energy of photoelectrons depends on ____ of incident light.</text>
            <option id="A">Frequency</option><option id="B">Intensity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Verified experimentally by Millikan.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Photoelectric current depends on ____ of incident light.</text>
            <option id="A">Intensity</option><option id="B">Frequency</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>More photons per second imply more electrons ejected.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Stopping potential V₀ is the potential difference at which photoelectric current becomes ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Maximum</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Negative potential applied to anode to stop fastest electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relation between Stopping Potential V₀ and Max KE is Kmax = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">e V₀</option><option id="B">V₀ / e</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy gained by electron in stopping potential field.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Stopping potential is independent of ____ of radiation.</text>
            <option id="A">Intensity</option><option id="B">Frequency</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>For a fixed frequency, multiple intensities have same V₀.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Photons are essentially quanta of ____ field.</text>
            <option id="A">Electromagnetic</option><option id="B">Gravitational</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Packets of EM energy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Speed of photon in vacuum is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">c (3 x 10^8 m/s)</option><option id="B">Less than c</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Propagate at speed of light.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Rest mass of a photon is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Finite</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Photons only exist in motion at speed c.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Linear momentum of a photon is p = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h / λ</option><option id="B">h λ</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>From E = pc and E = hc/λ.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Energy of a photon of frequency f is E = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h f</option><option id="B">h / f</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Planck's relation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Who proposed the matter-wave hypothesis?</text>
            <option id="A">De-Broglie</option><option id="B">Bohr</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Suggested particles exhibit wave nature (1924).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>De-Broglie wavelength of a particle of mass m and velocity v is λ = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h / (m v)</option><option id="B">m v / h</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>λ = h / p.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relation between λ and KE of a particle is λ = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h / √(2 m K)</option><option id="B">h / (2 m K)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>p = √(2mK).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>De-Broglie wavelength of an electron accelerated through V volts is approx λ = ____ / √V nm.</text>
            <option id="A">1.227</option><option id="B">12.27</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Numerical simplification for electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Davisson-Germer experiment confirmed the ____ nature of electrons.</text>
            <option id="A">Wave</option><option id="B">Particle</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Observed diffraction from nickel crystal.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Electrons are diffracted by crystals just like ____.</text>
            <option id="A">X-rays</option><option id="B">Radio waves</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Wavelength comparable to atomic spacing.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In photoelectric effect, emission occurs within ____ seconds of illumination.</text>
            <option id="A">10^-9 (Instantaneous)</option><option id="B">10^0 (Delayed)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Suggests direct collision of photons and electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Increase in intensity of incident light increases ____ of emission.</text>
            <option id="A">Number of electrons per second</option><option id="B">Speed of each electron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Intensity ∝ Rate of emission.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Work function of Alkali metals is ____ than that of other metals.</text>
            <option id="A">Lower</option><option id="B">Higher</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sensitive even to visible light.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Work function of Cesium is approx ____ eV.</text>
            <option id="A">2.14</option><option id="B">4.5</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>One of the lowest work functions.</explanation>
        </explanation>
        <question>
            <text>Heisenberg's Uncertainty Principle is related to ____ nature of matter.</text>
            <option id="A">Wave</option><option id="B">Particle only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Wave packets represent localization with spread in momentum.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Photons are electrically ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Neutral</option><option id="B">Positive</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Not deflected by electric/magnetic fields.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>An electron-microscope relies on ____ nature of electrons.</text>
            <option id="A">Wave</option><option id="B">Particle</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses shorter wavelength than light for higher resolution.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Energy of 1 eV is approx ____ Joules.</text>
            <option id="A">1.6 x 10^-19</option><option id="B">1.6 x 10^-27</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy of an electron through 1V potential.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which phenomenon supports wave nature of light?</text>
            <option id="A">Both Interference and Diffraction</option><option id="B">Photoelectric effect</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Classical wave properties.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which phenomenon supports particle nature of light?</text>
            <option id="A">Photoelectric effect</option><option id="B">Interference</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Requires discrete energy exchange.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A substance has rest mass m₀. Its mass at speed v is m = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">m₀ / √(1 - v²/c²)</option><option id="B">m₀ √(1 - v²/c²)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Relativistic mass increase.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ratio of energy to momentum for a photon is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">c (speed of light)</option><option id="B">1 / c</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>E = pc.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Photo-cell is a device that converts ____ energy into ____ energy.</text>
            <option id="A">Light, Electrical</option><option id="B">Electrical, Light</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on photoelectric effect.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Does the De-Broglie wavelength depend on the charge of the particle?</text>
            <option id="A">No (depends on p = mv)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>General formula λ = h/p.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A heavier particle from two particles with same velocity has ____ wavelength.</text>
            <option id="A">Shorter</option><option id="B">Longer</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>λ ∝ 1/m.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dual Nature initialization done.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Verified.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>If frequency of incident light is doubled, the stopping potential V₀ ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Becomes more than double</option><option id="B">Doubles</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>e V₀ = h f - Φ₀ => e V₀' = 2 h f - Φ₀ = 2(e V₀ + Φ₀) - Φ₀ = 2 e V₀ + Φ₀. V₀' = 2 V₀ + Φ₀/e.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Stopping potential depends on ____ but not on ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Frequency, Intensity</option><option id="B">Intensity, Frequency</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Intensity affects power, not energy per photon.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Slope of V₀ vs f graph for a photoelectric surface is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h / e</option><option id="B">e / h</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>V₀ = (h/e) f - Φ₀/e. Form y = mx + c.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Intercept on the frequency axis of V₀ vs f graph gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Threshold frequency (f₀)</option><option id="B">Work function</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>When V₀ = 0, f = f₀.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>If light of 300nm falls on a metal with Φ₀ = 2eV, Max KE is approx ____ eV.</text>
            <option id="A">2.13 (E = 1240/300 ≈ 4.13. K = 4.13 - 2)</option><option id="B">1.13</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using E(eV) ≈ 1240 / λ(nm).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>De-Broglie wavelength of a thermal neutron at temperature T is λ ∝ ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 / √T</option><option id="B">1 / T</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>K_avg = 3/2 k_B T. p = √(2mK) ∝ √T.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Comparison of λ of electron and proton with same KE: λ_e ____ λ_p.</text>
            <option id="A">> (λ ∝ 1/√m)</option><option id="B">&lt;</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electrons being lighter have larger wavelength.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Emission of electrons by applying a strong electric field to surface is ____ emission.</text>
            <option id="A">Field</option><option id="B">Secondary</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cold cathode emission by tunneling.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of photons emitted per second from a 60W source of 600nm is approx ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1.8 x 10^20</option><option id="B">10^15</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>n = P / (hc/λ). hc ≈ 2e-25. n = 60 / (2e-25 / 600e-9) = 1.8e20.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Does an increase in intensity shift the threshold frequency?</text>
            <option id="A">No</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>f₀ is a surface property.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Davisson and Germer used a ____ crystal to study electron diffraction.</text>
            <option id="A">Nickel</option><option id="B">Silicon</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Crystal lattice acted as a diffraction grating.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>For a given frequency, saturation current is proportional to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Intensity</option><option id="B">Distance from source only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>More photons ejecting more electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Momentum of an electron of wavelength 1 nm is approx ____ kg m/s.</text>
            <option id="A">6.63 x 10^-25</option><option id="B">10^-19</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>p = h / λ = 6.63e-34 / 1e-9.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The work function for a metal surface is 4 eV. The threshold wavelength is ____ nm.</text>
            <option id="A">310</option><option id="B">620</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>λ = 1240 / 4 = 310 nm.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Einstein's explanation of photoelectric effect assumes ____ collision between photon and electron.</text>
            <option id="A">One-to-one</option><option id="B">Multiple photons to one electron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Each photon delivers its entire energy to one electron.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Why is wave theory unable to explain threshold frequency?</text>
            <option id="A">In wave theory, intensity (energy per sec) alone should cause emission after time lag</option><option id="B">Wait, it does explain? No.</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy in wave is distributed; accumulation takes time regardless of frequency.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Davisson-Germer found max intensity at scattering angle ____ for 54V electrons.</text>
            <option id="A">50°</option><option id="B">90°</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Corresponded to constructive interference from nickel planes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Photoelectric current is independent of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Potential of anode once saturated</option><option id="B">Intensity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>All emitted electrons reach the anode.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Wave nature is dominant for ____ objects at high speeds.</text>
            <option id="A">Microscopic (like electrons)</option><option id="B">Macroscopic</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>For large m, λ is extremely small and undetectable.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>If a particle's momentum is doubled, its De-Broglie wavelength ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Is halved</option><option id="B">Is doubled</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>λ ∝ 1/p.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Maximum wavelength of incident radiation for which photoelectric effect occurs is λ₀. It corresponds to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Threshold wavelength</option><option id="B">Fringe width</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>λ₀ = c / f₀.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Slope of Kmax vs f graph is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">h (Planck's constant)</option><option id="B">e</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Kmax = h f - Φ₀. Form y = mx + c with m = h.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Is the slope of V₀ vs f graph same for all metals?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (is h/e, universal constant)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Only the intercept changes with material.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Photon momentum p and its energy E are related by p = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">E / c</option><option id="B">E / c²</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Since speed is c.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>An alpha particle and a proton have same velocity. λ_alpha / λ_proton = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 / 4</option><option id="B">4 / 1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>λ ∝ 1/m. m_alpha = 4 m_p.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Work function depends on ____ of the metal.</text>
            <option id="A">Nature and surface conditions</option><option id="B">Size</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Intrinsic property.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>What happens to stopping potential if frequency of incident light is increased but intensity is constant?</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Remains same</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Faster electrons requiring higher stopping field.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Energy of a quantum of light of wavelength λ is inversely proportional to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">λ</option><option id="B">f</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>E = hc / λ.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Davisson-Germer experiment used electrons of energy ____ eV for best results.</text>
            <option id="A">54</option><option id="B">100</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Matched wavelength for Bragg reflection peak.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>If Φ₀ increases, threshold frequency ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Φ₀ = h f₀.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Standardizing Dual Nature Medium section - in final stages.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Verified.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Wait, is there any time lag in wave theory explanation of photoelectric effect?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (major flaw)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Would take hours/days to accumulate 2eV from weak wave.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Is mass of a photon constant?</text>
            <option id="A">Depends on frequency (equivalent mass m = hf/c²)</option><option id="B">Yes, always 0</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Kinetic mass is hf/c². Rest mass is 0.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Momentum of a particle of energy E and mass m is p = √(____).</text>
            <option id="A">2 m E</option><option id="B">2 E / m</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard KE-momentum relation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Can we see matter waves of a car moving at 100 km/h?</text>
            <option id="A">No (λ is too small)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Too small to interact with any physical aperture.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dual nature means matter/radiation behaves as both ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Wave, Particle</option><option id="B">Alpha, Beta</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complementarity principle.</explanation>
